  "case_id": "D2N104",
  "method": "cap",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nOngoing management of psoriatic arthritis.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports ongoing management of psoriatic arthritis. She states that she's doing good, thank you. She reports that she's been taking one prednisone pill and that seems to be enough. She mentions a couple of days where she took an extra one because there was a little extra pain in her feet. She also reports that she has a desk job and when she's off and moving around a lot, her feet tend to hurt more. The patient reports that she took methotrexate, but she had a COVID shot and the letter said it could interfere with the vaccine, so she didn't take it the week she got her first shot. She felt absolutely horrible until she took it again a week later. The patient reports experiencing bruising and doesn't know where it's coming from. She also reports nail ridges and that they've been present for a long time. She has ongoing management of psoriatic arthritis.\n\nFindings\nExamination reveals good range of motion in the toes. Nail ridges are present. The patient reports pain in the left hand and feet. The patient reports pain.\n\nAssessment\nThe patient has psoriatic arthritis. The patient is taking prednisone and methotrexate.\n\nPlan\nWe will discontinue prednisone and continue with methotrexate. Make sure to schedule an appointment for blood work. I'll see you in three months. ,",
  "reference_summary": "CHIEF COMPLAINT\n\nPsoriatic arthritis management.\n\nHISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS\n\nJudy Gomez is a 61-year-old female who presents to the clinic today for ongoing management of psoriatic arthritis.\n\nMs. Gomez is currently taking methotrexate and prednisone 1 mg daily. She believes methotrexate has been relieving her joint pain.\n\nThe patient reports she has been doing well since her last visit. She has been able to decrease her prednisone dose to 1 mg daily; however, she took 2 mg for a couple of days due to increased pain in her bilateral feet.\n\nThe patient states when she received her first COVID-19 vaccine she held her methotrexate and felt \"horrible\" all week until the next Wednesday when she took it. She felt better by the end of the week. She did not hold methotrexate for her second COVID-19 vaccine.\n\nPHYSICAL EXAM\n\nMusculoskeletal: Full range of motion. Dystrophy of all the nails of the toes.\n\nASSESSMENT\n\n• Psoriatic arthritis.\n• High risk medication use.\n\nPLAN\n\nPsoriatic arthritis.\nStable on methotrexate and prednisone 1 mg daily. The patient will discontinue prednisone and continue methotrexate.\n\nINSTRUCTIONS\n\nThe patient will follow up in 3 months.",
